1
00:00:06,202 --> 00:00:07,842
All right, welcome everyone.

2
00:00:07,842 --> 00:00:09,783
So my name is Daniel Brewer,

3
00:00:09,783 --> 00:00:11,544
and this is my co-presenter, Rez Graham.

4
00:00:11,544 --> 00:00:14,805
Here at the Summit over the years,

5
00:00:14,805 --> 00:00:16,746
we've spent a lot of time discussing

6
00:00:16,746 --> 00:00:18,367
how agents make decisions,

7
00:00:18,367 --> 00:00:20,468
all of sexy different algorithms.

8
00:00:20,468 --> 00:00:25,070
But one thing that we don't spend enough time on

9
00:00:25,070 --> 00:00:28,692
is the data that is used to make these decisions

10
00:00:28,692 --> 00:00:29,352
by these algorithms.

11
00:00:29,352 --> 00:00:31,853
And the quality of these decisions

12
00:00:31,853 --> 00:00:33,794
is far more dependent on this data

13
00:00:33,794 --> 00:00:35,575
than it is on whatever algorithm you're using.

14
00:00:36,775 --> 00:00:39,756
So today we're gonna talk about knowledge representation.

15
00:00:39,756 --> 00:00:42,077
And I can see some of you nodding off already

16
00:00:42,077 --> 00:00:43,437
at the back there.

17
00:00:43,437 --> 00:00:44,037
But stay with us.

18
00:00:44,037 --> 00:00:48,699
So we're gonna provide an overview of some common techniques

19
00:00:48,699 --> 00:00:50,060
used to provide data to agents

20
00:00:50,060 --> 00:00:52,080
and show how richer behaviors can be crafted

21
00:00:52,080 --> 00:00:53,481
by paying attention to this data.

22
00:00:53,481 --> 00:00:58,583
So if the slides will work, there we go.

23
00:01:00,151 --> 00:01:03,193
When the players are playing your game, this is what they see.

24
00:01:03,193 --> 00:01:06,376
And the human brain is amazing at taking this input,

25
00:01:06,376 --> 00:01:09,559
identifying the important bits, and then deciding what to do.

26
00:01:09,559 --> 00:01:13,982
But this is what our agents see when they're playing your game.

27
00:01:13,982 --> 00:01:18,186
Or maybe it's a little bit more like this.

28
00:01:18,186 --> 00:01:22,129
Our game worlds are made up of structs and pointers

29
00:01:22,129 --> 00:01:23,510
and polygons and textures.

30
00:01:23,510 --> 00:01:27,113
And we need our agents to interpret all of this

31
00:01:27,113 --> 00:01:28,574
to identify the important bits.

32
00:01:29,388 --> 00:01:32,530
to see the patterns in the matrix, right?

33
00:01:32,530 --> 00:01:34,011
Blonde, brunette, redhead.

34
00:01:34,011 --> 00:01:40,675
And so we need to provide our agents with the information

35
00:01:40,675 --> 00:01:44,378
they need to allow them to make better decisions

36
00:01:44,378 --> 00:01:46,999
and exhibit the behavior that the designer wants.

37
00:01:46,999 --> 00:01:49,301
And it's helpful to think about this behavior falling

38
00:01:49,301 --> 00:01:51,542
into three broad categories.

39
00:01:51,542 --> 00:01:54,724
Static environment data, dynamic spatial data, and then

40
00:01:54,724 --> 00:01:55,905
entity information.

41
00:01:58,737 --> 00:02:01,858
So static environment data, as the name suggests,

42
00:02:01,858 --> 00:02:06,100
is kind of representing the physical world to your agents.

43
00:02:06,100 --> 00:02:07,921
This data typically does not change

44
00:02:07,921 --> 00:02:10,882
a hell of a lot at runtime,

45
00:02:10,882 --> 00:02:14,423
and your agents use this really predominantly

46
00:02:14,423 --> 00:02:16,224
to find their way around or search for positions.

47
00:02:16,224 --> 00:02:20,786
Navigation and pathfinding are some

48
00:02:20,786 --> 00:02:22,827
of AI's eternal problem spaces.

49
00:02:23,827 --> 00:02:25,147
As environments grow more complex

50
00:02:25,147 --> 00:02:27,728
and the movement requirements get more crazy,

51
00:02:27,728 --> 00:02:30,049
the representation of the navigable space

52
00:02:30,049 --> 00:02:31,269
needs to get more complex too.

53
00:02:31,269 --> 00:02:33,690
It's this bit of an arms race between graphics programmers

54
00:02:33,690 --> 00:02:34,550
and AI programmers.

55
00:02:34,550 --> 00:02:38,832
So agents are no longer just merely required

56
00:02:38,832 --> 00:02:43,153
to wander around the level in open boxes.

57
00:02:43,153 --> 00:02:46,274
If we take this kind of simple environment here,

58
00:02:46,274 --> 00:02:47,935
it's an open square,

59
00:02:47,935 --> 00:02:50,496
but our designers will usually throw a challenge at us.

60
00:02:53,570 --> 00:02:56,571
So we need to have a way for our agents to know

61
00:02:56,571 --> 00:02:58,071
that they can stay on the pathways,

62
00:02:58,071 --> 00:02:59,951
but they shouldn't go in the grass.

63
00:02:59,951 --> 00:03:03,512
However, if a student is late for class

64
00:03:03,512 --> 00:03:04,753
and there's no professors around,

65
00:03:04,753 --> 00:03:07,873
or maybe the school is under attack by space aliens,

66
00:03:07,873 --> 00:03:09,374
then they're gonna run across that grass anyway,

67
00:03:09,374 --> 00:03:10,114
because who gives a damn?

68
00:03:10,114 --> 00:03:16,216
So if using a grid for your navigation representation,

69
00:03:16,216 --> 00:03:18,396
it's relatively simple, right?

70
00:03:18,396 --> 00:03:20,117
You can mark up each cell in your grid

71
00:03:20,117 --> 00:03:21,717
with the terrain type.

72
00:03:22,687 --> 00:03:24,547
And then you can construct a cost function

73
00:03:24,547 --> 00:03:27,308
that will guide your agent along the pathways.

74
00:03:27,308 --> 00:03:30,008
When you're using a nav mesh, however,

75
00:03:30,008 --> 00:03:31,749
things are a little bit different.

76
00:03:31,749 --> 00:03:33,769
A typical nav mesh might look like this,

77
00:03:33,769 --> 00:03:35,569
but this isn't good enough

78
00:03:35,569 --> 00:03:37,330
because we don't know where anything is here.

79
00:03:37,330 --> 00:03:40,951
So we need to provide some tools to our designers

80
00:03:40,951 --> 00:03:43,331
to allow them to mark up this environment

81
00:03:43,331 --> 00:03:46,632
so that they can tell the agents where the grass is

82
00:03:46,632 --> 00:03:47,832
and where the walkways are.

83
00:03:48,505 --> 00:03:50,327
and then we're good to go from there, right?

84
00:03:50,327 --> 00:03:53,369
This is adding more complexity to our navigation graph,

85
00:03:53,369 --> 00:03:55,671
but as we've seen from the Horizon talk earlier

86
00:03:55,671 --> 00:03:56,532
and Nathan's talk,

87
00:03:56,532 --> 00:03:59,234
adding this extra weight and markup

88
00:03:59,234 --> 00:04:00,054
does help with the behaviors.

89
00:04:00,054 --> 00:04:03,837
We use this technique in the darkness too.

90
00:04:03,837 --> 00:04:07,660
Back in the day, we actually created cutting volumes

91
00:04:07,660 --> 00:04:10,903
from the light cones and cut our NavMesh with those volumes,

92
00:04:10,903 --> 00:04:13,344
and then we measured the illumination and marked that up,

93
00:04:13,344 --> 00:04:15,146
and that allowed our darkling character

94
00:04:15,146 --> 00:04:16,827
to remain in the shadows and avoid the lights.

95
00:04:19,744 --> 00:04:26,147
And then once you have this information in your representation,

96
00:04:26,147 --> 00:04:28,027
it's relatively easy then to construct a different,

97
00:04:28,027 --> 00:04:31,849
choose a different cost function depending on what behavior you want to run.

98
00:04:33,131 --> 00:04:36,092
If you use an ID to represent your terrain,

99
00:04:36,092 --> 00:04:39,072
then you're kind of restricted to only using

100
00:04:39,072 --> 00:04:41,813
a single type of consideration at a time.

101
00:04:41,813 --> 00:04:46,214
Whereas if you use a bit mask to represent your terrain types,

102
00:04:46,214 --> 00:04:49,334
you can then start combining these different weighting

103
00:04:49,334 --> 00:04:54,175
factions together.

104
00:04:54,175 --> 00:04:56,496
Now, moving along, smart objects are

105
00:04:56,496 --> 00:04:58,936
one of the unsung heroes of a game AI knowledge

106
00:04:58,936 --> 00:04:59,596
representation.

107
00:05:00,299 --> 00:05:02,960
The Sims is really the poster child here

108
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:04,620
for how smart objects can be used

109
00:05:04,620 --> 00:05:06,741
to extend the capabilities of agents

110
00:05:06,741 --> 00:05:09,601
and make them seem much more aware of their environment.

111
00:05:09,601 --> 00:05:13,122
But we can use them all over the place in other games too.

112
00:05:13,122 --> 00:05:16,003
F.E.A.R. used this to great effect.

113
00:05:16,003 --> 00:05:19,443
At the essence, a smart object is an abstraction

114
00:05:19,443 --> 00:05:23,044
and it encapsulates some arbitrarily complex logic

115
00:05:23,044 --> 00:05:24,305
behind a simple interface.

116
00:05:24,305 --> 00:05:26,445
And it ties that to a particular location

117
00:05:26,445 --> 00:05:27,265
or entity in the world.

118
00:05:28,023 --> 00:05:30,485
And now your agents don't need to know any of that complex

119
00:05:30,485 --> 00:05:31,065
information.

120
00:05:31,065 --> 00:05:32,666
They just need to know, they just

121
00:05:32,666 --> 00:05:35,247
need to select which smart object to use.

122
00:05:35,247 --> 00:05:37,489
And all the data, all that logic is

123
00:05:37,489 --> 00:05:39,089
embedded in that smart object.

124
00:05:39,089 --> 00:05:43,812
So all you need to do to make your games have raving AI

125
00:05:43,812 --> 00:05:52,136
reviews is just add smart objects to your game.

126
00:05:52,136 --> 00:05:55,718
Now, a lot of decisions in action and strategy games

127
00:05:55,718 --> 00:05:56,459
revolve around.

128
00:05:57,177 --> 00:06:00,379
where should the agent move and how we should get there.

129
00:06:00,379 --> 00:06:03,241
So it's beneficial to have an understanding

130
00:06:03,241 --> 00:06:05,222
of the overall flow and structure of the level.

131
00:06:05,222 --> 00:06:07,364
What are the main regions of the map?

132
00:06:07,364 --> 00:06:08,624
How are these regions connected?

133
00:06:08,624 --> 00:06:11,746
Where are the choke points?

134
00:06:11,746 --> 00:06:14,468
So your navigation representation can certainly help here,

135
00:06:14,468 --> 00:06:15,629
but it's often too detailed.

136
00:06:15,629 --> 00:06:17,830
It's like trying to find the forest amidst all the trees.

137
00:06:17,830 --> 00:06:21,453
So it's useful to have a higher level representation.

138
00:06:22,459 --> 00:06:26,583
In Warframe, we use a rough corridor map as our structure

139
00:06:26,583 --> 00:06:27,964
to represent this information.

140
00:06:27,964 --> 00:06:29,085
We call it our tactical map.

141
00:06:29,085 --> 00:06:33,589
And it represents the flow of the level at runtime.

142
00:06:33,589 --> 00:06:37,012
We add a whole lot of extra markup into this graph.

143
00:06:37,012 --> 00:06:38,973
We know where all the doors are and what state they're in.

144
00:06:38,973 --> 00:06:40,835
We add our cover points and spawn points in there.

145
00:06:40,835 --> 00:06:43,137
A whole lot of different systems use it.

146
00:06:43,137 --> 00:06:45,539
Our AI director uses it.

147
00:06:45,539 --> 00:06:48,421
The NPCs use this to find cover and to patrol.

148
00:06:49,008 --> 00:06:53,549
The designers can write scripts that'll search through this graph to find objective locations.

149
00:06:53,549 --> 00:06:59,812
It's a very useful abstract representation for the level.

150
00:06:59,812 --> 00:07:04,613
Now dynamic spatial data is used for representing spatial relationships that are affected by

151
00:07:04,613 --> 00:07:06,274
the environment and change over time.

152
00:07:06,274 --> 00:07:10,535
So even though the physical structure of your level may be static,

153
00:07:11,249 --> 00:07:13,610
The positioning of units can change at runtime,

154
00:07:13,610 --> 00:07:17,392
and this will create a lot of dynamic situations.

155
00:07:17,392 --> 00:07:19,493
And it's useful to be able to predict and react

156
00:07:19,493 --> 00:07:21,114
to these situations.

157
00:07:21,114 --> 00:07:25,416
So this is where it's useful to have some map of values

158
00:07:25,416 --> 00:07:28,538
tied to specific areas in the map that represent information

159
00:07:28,538 --> 00:07:30,819
and allow that to flow through your map,

160
00:07:30,819 --> 00:07:32,640
through the environment, and respond to it.

161
00:07:34,411 --> 00:07:38,372
Influence maps are really the go-to algorithm here,

162
00:07:38,372 --> 00:07:41,613
and Dave is going to give a huge talk tomorrow about it.

163
00:07:41,613 --> 00:07:42,734
It's an hour and three minutes, I think.

164
00:07:42,734 --> 00:07:46,655
So I'm not going to go into detail on them,

165
00:07:46,655 --> 00:07:47,936
but I'm just going to cover a couple of uses

166
00:07:47,936 --> 00:07:50,217
that we found useful in Warframe.

167
00:07:50,217 --> 00:07:54,078
Firstly, instead of just spreading out influence

168
00:07:54,078 --> 00:07:58,059
from your characters, you can insert influence

169
00:07:58,059 --> 00:08:01,120
where characters take damage or where they die,

170
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:02,281
and now you've got a danger map.

171
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,583
And you can use this to draw enemies into the conflict zone

172
00:08:06,583 --> 00:08:08,705
as reinforcements, or you can push enemies away,

173
00:08:08,705 --> 00:08:10,346
characters away from that conflict zone.

174
00:08:12,397 --> 00:08:14,698
You can also simulate environmental hazards

175
00:08:14,698 --> 00:08:17,040
like a hull breach in a spaceship.

176
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:19,642
Right, when you get a window blown out,

177
00:08:19,642 --> 00:08:22,323
you can source some influence from that window

178
00:08:22,323 --> 00:08:24,985
and spread that out through your influence map.

179
00:08:24,985 --> 00:08:27,427
We run our influence maps on our tactical map

180
00:08:27,427 --> 00:08:28,488
so we know where the doors are,

181
00:08:28,488 --> 00:08:30,229
we know what state the doors are in,

182
00:08:30,229 --> 00:08:33,211
and then we can modify our spread of this influence

183
00:08:33,211 --> 00:08:36,573
so that the doors will contain that vacuum in those areas.

184
00:08:37,074 --> 00:08:42,058
And you can use this for fire or floods or any other environmental feature that can spread

185
00:08:42,058 --> 00:08:42,439
through the map.

186
00:08:42,439 --> 00:08:49,044
An objective distance map is useful for knowing where the objectives are.

187
00:08:49,044 --> 00:08:54,149
You can see all the objectives in the level with a distance of zero and then use Dijkstra

188
00:08:54,149 --> 00:08:58,372
to flood fill out the distance from any point in the map to that objective.

189
00:08:58,372 --> 00:08:59,513
Now you've got a table lookup.

190
00:09:00,314 --> 00:09:04,856
and you know how far away you are, an approximation for how far away you are from the closest objective.

191
00:09:04,856 --> 00:09:08,038
You know which direction to go to get to that objective.

192
00:09:08,038 --> 00:09:12,780
You can make your NPCs take cover between the players and the objective.

193
00:09:12,780 --> 00:09:16,041
We use this a huge number of different ways.

194
00:09:16,041 --> 00:09:23,225
And now you can also pay attention to the changes in influence and start to make predictions.

195
00:09:24,327 --> 00:09:26,950
So if influence is spreading out from your characters,

196
00:09:26,950 --> 00:09:29,593
as your characters move, the influence

197
00:09:29,593 --> 00:09:32,075
is going to be rising up in the areas ahead of where

198
00:09:32,075 --> 00:09:35,259
they're moving, and it'll be dropping down behind them.

199
00:09:35,259 --> 00:09:37,461
So by looking for areas that have a positive change

200
00:09:37,461 --> 00:09:40,264
in influence, you can predict where the player is headed.

201
00:09:40,264 --> 00:09:42,406
And that is also quite useful.

202
00:09:46,643 --> 00:09:49,845
Entity data is data that's used to make decisions

203
00:09:49,845 --> 00:09:51,445
about the other active entities in your game.

204
00:09:51,445 --> 00:09:54,906
And this is the broadest and most varied type of knowledge

205
00:09:54,906 --> 00:09:57,807
that you have to deal with, and it's also highly dependent

206
00:09:57,807 --> 00:09:59,768
on the type of game you're making.

207
00:09:59,768 --> 00:10:01,929
In an action game, this is usually information

208
00:10:01,929 --> 00:10:03,249
about the possible targets.

209
00:10:03,249 --> 00:10:05,850
In a racing game, it's gonna be information

210
00:10:05,850 --> 00:10:07,650
about the other race cars.

211
00:10:07,650 --> 00:10:09,471
In a high strategy game, this could be information

212
00:10:09,471 --> 00:10:11,352
about the other civilizations,

213
00:10:11,352 --> 00:10:13,072
what technologies they've developed,

214
00:10:13,072 --> 00:10:14,513
what resources they have to trade.

215
00:10:17,349 --> 00:10:20,091
From my background, I've been focusing more on action games,

216
00:10:20,091 --> 00:10:22,533
so that's what I'm gonna talk about here.

217
00:10:22,533 --> 00:10:24,695
And here you'll want to track information

218
00:10:24,695 --> 00:10:26,136
about possible targets.

219
00:10:26,136 --> 00:10:28,518
And usually you'll have some perception system

220
00:10:28,518 --> 00:10:31,340
that feeds you information about which targets

221
00:10:31,340 --> 00:10:34,683
your agent is aware of and what he knows about them.

222
00:10:34,683 --> 00:10:37,986
And you can maintain this information in a target list.

223
00:10:37,986 --> 00:10:39,927
And this is basically just an array of structs

224
00:10:39,927 --> 00:10:41,729
with the information that you know about those targets.

225
00:10:43,630 --> 00:10:48,295
Now there's two important reasons why you'd want to separate your knowledge like this.

226
00:10:48,295 --> 00:10:55,822
And firstly, caching this information from the world allows you to separate your AI systems

227
00:10:55,822 --> 00:11:01,146
from your world and it allows you to run things asynchronously more easily because then you

228
00:11:01,146 --> 00:11:05,631
don't have that dependency of your AI system pulling stuff directly from the world.

229
00:11:05,631 --> 00:11:10,075
And secondly, if your agent only has access to the information he has perceived...

230
00:11:10,925 --> 00:11:13,905
It allows your players to play tricks on your agents.

231
00:11:13,905 --> 00:11:15,166
He can manipulate them.

232
00:11:15,166 --> 00:11:17,506
And that's starting to get where the fun in game design is.

233
00:11:17,506 --> 00:11:20,367
So what information should you store?

234
00:11:20,367 --> 00:11:23,087
Well, at the very least, you need to know

235
00:11:23,087 --> 00:11:24,568
that your target is visible or not,

236
00:11:24,568 --> 00:11:26,228
what his last known position is.

237
00:11:26,228 --> 00:11:28,529
Splinter Cell does a great job of that.

238
00:11:28,529 --> 00:11:30,529
It can be useful to have the time since seen as well,

239
00:11:30,529 --> 00:11:32,990
because that allows you to have a little bit

240
00:11:32,990 --> 00:11:35,890
of extra robustness against a temporary obstruction.

241
00:11:37,756 --> 00:11:42,058
Additionally, it's useful to keep track of the type of information perceived.

242
00:11:42,058 --> 00:11:47,240
If an agent hears a noise, you don't want it to go straight into combat or run for the

243
00:11:47,240 --> 00:11:48,380
alarm.

244
00:11:48,380 --> 00:11:52,882
You want them to first turn around and react to see the source of that noise first.

245
00:11:52,882 --> 00:11:54,963
And we saw an example of that in the previous talk.

246
00:11:54,963 --> 00:11:59,965
If you're sharing information amongst agents, it's useful to know whether the information

247
00:11:59,965 --> 00:12:02,206
you have is first-hand or second-hand.

248
00:12:03,684 --> 00:12:06,846
because a hidden agent that the player can't see,

249
00:12:06,846 --> 00:12:10,148
if he ran for the alarm based on the second-hand information,

250
00:12:10,148 --> 00:12:12,370
it wouldn't feel fair to the player.

251
00:12:12,370 --> 00:12:15,492
The player has no idea that that other agent was there.

252
00:12:15,492 --> 00:12:18,834
So it would be better for the first agent,

253
00:12:18,834 --> 00:12:20,855
who does see the player first-hand,

254
00:12:20,855 --> 00:12:22,696
to run for the alarm.

255
00:12:22,696 --> 00:12:25,138
This is more believable to the player,

256
00:12:25,138 --> 00:12:27,499
and it also allows your player the opportunity

257
00:12:27,499 --> 00:12:29,681
to stop that guy from triggering the alarm,

